{{EngvarB|date=December 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}} {{Infobox civilian attack | image= Panorama Sengkotek, Samarinda.jpg | caption= Oikumene Church in Sengkotek, Samarinda, the location of the bombing | title = 2016 Samarinda church bombing | location = Oikumene Church, Sengkotek, Samarinda Seberang, Samarinda, East Kalimantan, Indonesia | target = Civilians, Christians | date = 13 November 2016 | time= 10:10 [[Time in Indonesia|WITA]] | timezone = [[UTC+8]] | type = [[Bombing]], [[Murder]] | fatalities = 1 | injuries = 4 (including the perpetrator) | motive = | perp = [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] | assailants = Juhanda | numparts = 5 | weapons = [[Molotov cocktail|Molotov bomb]] }}
The '''2016 Samarinda Church bombing''' was a [[Terrorism|terrorist attack]] that occurred on 13 November 2016 when Juhanda as the perpetrator detonated a [[Molotov cocktail|Molotov bomb]] in front of Oikumene Church in Samarinda Seberang, [[Samarinda]], [[East Kalimantan]], [[Indonesia]], where children were playing. At least 1 toddler was killed in the incident and 3 other toddlers were injured. In September 2017, Juhanda and four others were convicted of the attack, with Juhanda sentenced to life imprisonment, while the others received sentences ranging from six to seven years.
The bombing was the second attack on church in Indonesia in 2016, with the first attack occurred in [[Medan]] on August when an [[Islamic State of Iraq and Syria|ISIS]] sympathiser attacked a priest during a mass. It was also the second terror attack to occur in less than a month, after another [[Islamic State of Iraq and Syria|ISIS]] sympathiser was shot dead after wounding 3 police officers with a machete in [[Tangerang]].
==Bombing== The explosion occurred on 10:10 WITA (Central Indonesian Time), on Oikumene Church located on Dr. Cipto Mangunkusumo Road in Sengkotek, Loa Janan Ilir District, Samarinda. Oikumene Church is the most popular church in Sengkotek.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ferdinan|title=Terjadi Ledakan di Depan Gereja Oikumene Samarinda|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3344053/terjadi-ledakan-di-depan-gereja-oikumene-samarinda|publisher=''Detik''|accessdate=13 November 2016|language=Indonesian}}</ref> At the time, the prayer service had just finished and crowds were getting out from the church. Prosecutors said Juhanda traveled to the church by motorbike, carrying a bag full of black explosive powder and a fuse, intending to cause mass casualties. But instead it exploded when he fell from the bike in front of the church, where children were playing.<ref name="abc-seeklife">{{cite news|last1=Hawley|first1=Samantha|title=Indonesian prosecutors seek life sentence for church bomber accused of killing toddler|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-09-01/indonesian-church-bomber-deserves-life-in-jail-prosecutors-say/8861454|accessdate=26 September 2017|work=ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|date=1 September 2017}}</ref><ref name="jp-sentencing">{{cite news|title=Extremist sentenced to life for Samarinda church attack|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2017/09/25/extremist-sentence-to-life-for-samarinda-church-attack.html|accessdate=26 September 2017|work=The Jakarta Post|agency=Agence France-Presse|date=25 September 2017}}</ref> 4 toddlers were injured in the explosion. Juhanda immediately ran away, but later was caught by locals and people from the church after he fell into [[Mahakam River]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Amelia R, Mei|title=Kapolda Kaltim: Pelempar Bom Molotov Depan Gereja Oikumene Sudah Ditangkap|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3344083/kapolda-kaltim-pelempar-bom-molotov-depan-gereja-oikumene-sudah-ditangkap|publisher=''Detik''|accessdate=13 November 2016|language=Indonesian}}</ref>
[[File:Rumah Sakit Umum Daerah I.A. Moeis.jpg|thumb|The injured were immediately taken to Samarinda's I.A Moeis Hospital]] Firefighters, Indonesian National Police and its bomb disposal unit were immediately dispatched after the bombing. The injured, all of them toddlers with age ranging from 2 - 4 year old, were immediately taken by emergency services to Samarinda's main hospital, I.A Moeis Hospital. People from the church were evacuated from the area after the explosion. 2 toddlers were critically injured in the incident. On 14 November, the next day of the bombing, 2 year old Olivia Intan Marbun Banjarnahor, succumbed to her wounds and became the only fatality in the attack.<ref>{{cite web|title=Satu Korban Ledakan Bom Molotov di depan Gereja Samarinda Meninggal Dunia|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3344469/satu-korban-ledakan-bom-molotov-di-depan-gereja-samarinda-meninggal-dunia|publisher=''Detik''|accessdate=14 November 2016|language=Indonesian}}</ref>
==Perpetrator== The perpetrator was identified by the Indonesian National Police as Juhanda, who had only been released from jail a few months before the Samarinda attack, convicted of attempted terror attack in Christ Cathedral in Jakarta, and a series of "book bombings" where explosives were hidden in books and sent to activists, both occurring in 2011.<ref name="abc-seeklife" /> At the time, he joined a terrorist group identified by the police as Pepy Vernando.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pelempar Bom di Depan Gereja Samarinda Mantan Napi Teroris|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3344156/pelempar-bom-di-depan-gereja-samarinda-mantan-napi-teroris|publisher=Detik|accessdate=14 November 2016|language=Indonesian}}</ref> Before he lived in Samarinda, he settled in Bogor. He moved to Samarinda in 2015 and worked in local mosque.<ref>{{cite web|title=Polisi Telusuri Jaringan Pelaku Pengeboman di Depan Gereja Oikumene Samarinda|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3344145/polisi-telusuri-jaringan-pelaku-pengeboman-di-depan-gereja-oikumene-samarinda|publisher=Detik|accessdate=14 November 2016|language=Indonesian}}</ref> Juhanda was noticed by people shortly before the attack using a "Jihad, Way of life" T-shirt outside the church. He was sentenced to 3 years and 6 months in prison by the Jakarta's Civil Court on 29 February 2012. In July 2014, Juhanda was released<ref>{{cite web|title=Pelempar Bom Molotov di Depan Gereja Samarinda Bebas Dari Bui Juli 2014|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3344228/pelempar-bom-molotov-di-depan-gereja-samarinda-bebas-dari-bui-juli-2014|publisher=Detik|accessdate=14 November 2016|language=Indonesian}}</ref> due to Eid Al-Fitr remission and immediately joined another terrorist group in East Kalimantan, named as the JAD, which has a link with the Anshori Group, another terrorist group that could bring weapons from the [[Philippines]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}
On 25 September 2017, Juhanda was sentenced to life imprisonment. Juhanda was arrested and convicted along with four others, all five accused of belonging to the JAD group. The others received sentences ranging from six to seven years.<ref name="jp-sentencing" />
==Aftermath== Immediately after the incident, several high Muslim organisations in Indonesia, such as [[Nahdlatul Ulama]] and [[Indonesian Ulema Council]] (MUI) condemned the bombing, with MUI calling Intan's death as "a tragedy of humanity". President Joko Widodo immediately ordered the Indonesian National Police for a fully thorough investigation into the incident.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jokowi: Usut Tuntas Pelemparan Bom Molotov di Depan Gereja di Samarinda|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3344336/jokowi-usut-tuntas-pelemparan-bom-molotov-di-depan-gereja-di-samarinda|publisher=Detik|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref> The Chief of the Indonesian National Police General Tito Karnavian immediately stated to all Indonesians to "not panic" after the attack and stay calm.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ada Teror Bom di Depan Gereja Samarinda, Kapolri Imbau Masyarakat Tenang|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3344203/bom-meledak-di-depan-gereja-samarinda-polri-tetap-tenang-jangan-terpancing|publisher=Detik|accessdate=14 November 2016}}</ref> The Minister of Internal Affairs, Tjahjo Kumolo, immediately called the bombing as a terror attack.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bom di Depan Gereja Samarinda, Mendagri: Ini Teror pada Masyarakat|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3344244/bom-di-depan-gereja-samarinda-mendagri-ini-teror-pada-masyarakat|publisher=Detik}}</ref> Jakarta's Religions Tolerance Forum condemned the bombing, calling it as "inhumane".<ref>{{cite web|title=FKUB DKI Jakarta Kutuk Pelemparan Bom Molotov di Depan Gereja Samarinda|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3345228/fkub-dki-jakarta-kutuk-pelemparan-bom-molotov-di-depan-gereja-samarinda}}</ref>
Security measures were immediately taken after the bombing. Indonesian National Police ordered security measures to be taken in Oikumene Church after the bombing. Similar measures were taken in churches in [[Medan]] and [[Yogyakarta]]. The Vice Governor of East Java stated that the East Java Government, including the police, Indonesian National Soldier and Ulema to stay alert after the incident, and taken a "precaution steps" in order to detect terrorism in the region.<ref>{{cite web|title=Antisipasi Teror, Wagub Jatim: Kewaspadaan Kita Tingkatkan|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3344407/antisipasi-teror-wagub-jatim-kewaspadaan-kita-tingkatkan}}</ref>
Shortly after the news of Intan's death broke, hashtag #RIPIntan went viral on social media, with many Indonesians shared their disbelief and condemned the attack, especially knowing that the victim was a toddler. News articles and media in Indonesia immediately stated their sorrows and regrets for "not guarding Intan". Thousands of condolences were sent to Intan's relatives and next of kin. Those who sent condolences include President Joko Widodo,<ref>{{cite web|title=#RIPIntan, Jokowi: Meninggalnya Intan di Luar Batas Kemanusiaan|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3345855/ripintan-jokowi-meninggalnya-intan-di-luar-batas-kemanusiaan}}</ref> [[Ridwan Kamil]], and many other political figures in Indonesia. On 14 November, a candlelight vigil, attended by hundreds of people, was held in Hotel Indonesia Roundabout (Bundaran HI) in Jakarta. Similar vigils were held throughout Indonesia, including in Samarinda and Pontianak.<ref>{{cite web|title=RIP Intan: Seribu Lilin untuk Menerangi Jalan Intan Menuju Surga|url=http://bangka.tribunnews.com/2016/11/14/rip-intan-seribu-lilin-untuk-menerangi-jalan-intan-menuju-surga}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=RIP Intan: Maafkan Kami yang Gagal Melindungimu|url=http://bangka.tribunnews.com/2016/11/14/rip-intan-maafkan-kami-yang-gagal-melindungimu?page=2}}</ref> In [[Manado]], the vigil was attended by hundreds of people from many religious beliefs. In [[Ambon Island|Ambon]], a peace rally was held immediately after the blast. Shortly after the incident, Muslim volunteers in Samarinda joined churchgoers to clean their church. Tolerance were shown between Muslims and non-Muslims in Purwakarta, [[Banyuwangi]] and [[Papua Province|Papua]].<ref>https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3349166/menyejukkan-potret-toleransi-beragama-dari-samarinda-hingga-papua/2</ref> A painting dedicated for Intan, depicting Intan as an angel with wings behind her back, immediately went viral after the incident.<ref>{{cite web|title=#RIPIntan, Lukisan Intan Olivia Korban Bom Samarinda Ini Viral di Medsos|url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3346034/ripintan-lukisan-intan-olivia-korban-bom-samarinda-ini-viral-di-medsos}}</ref>
