{{For|the Papuan language known as "Je"|Yei language}} {{Infobox language family |name=Jê |altname=Jê–Kaingang, Gê, Ye |ethnicity=[[Gê peoples]] |region=[[Brazil]] |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Macro-Jê languages|Macro-Jê]] |glotto=jeee1236 |glottorefname=Je |child1=Central Jê |child2=Jeikó |child3=Northern Jê |child4=Southern Jê |map=Macro-Ge languages.png |mapcaption=Jê languages proper (clear yellow) and other Macro-Jê languages (dark yellow) in modern times. Shadowed area represent approximately extension in the past. }}
The '''Jê languages''' (also spelled '''Gê''', '''Jean''', '''Ye''', '''Gean'''), or '''Jê–Kaingang languages''', are spoken by the [[Gê peoples|Gê]], a group of [[indigenous peoples in Brazil]].
==Family division==
According to Ethnologue (which omits Jeikó), the language family is as follows:
* [[Jeikó language|Jeikó]] (†) * Northern Jê ** [[Apinayé language|Apinayé]] ** [[Mẽbengokre language|Mẽbengokre]] (Kayapó) ** [[Panará language|Panará]] (Kreen Akarore) ** [[Suya language|Suyá]] ** [[Timbira language|Timbira]] (Canela-Krayô, with the [[Canela language|Canela]] and [[Kreye language|Kreye]] dialects) * Central Jê ** [[Acroá language|Acroá]] (†) ** [[Xavante language|Xavante]] ** [[Xerente language|Xerente]] ** [[Xakriabá language|Xakriabá]] (†) * Southern Jê ** [[Xokleng language|Xokleng]] ** Kaingáng *** [[Kaingang language|Kaingáng]] *** [[São Paulo Kaingáng language|São Paulo Kaingáng]] (†) *** [[Ingain language|Ingain]] (†) *** [[Guayana language|Guayana]] (†)
==Genetic relations== The Jê family forms the core of the [[Macro-Jê]] family. Kaufman (1990) finds the proposal convincing.
